1
00:00:01,234 --> 00:00:03,568
[Waves lapping]

2
00:00:12,678 --> 00:00:14,779
[Helicopter]

3
00:00:25,624 --> 00:00:28,427
Colonel Chadwick sent me!
We got a Code Orange!

4
00:00:28,494 --> 00:00:29,661
We got a big storm
coming in!

5
00:00:29,728 --> 00:00:31,496
I got a problem
in the pump room!

6
00:00:33,533 --> 00:00:34,566
Let's go.

7
00:00:34,633 --> 00:00:39,037
Yeah, so sounds like
you got a punch-through.

8
00:00:39,105 --> 00:00:40,972
We've hit
a geologic formation.

9
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:42,240
Gas?

10
00:00:42,308 --> 00:00:43,341
Something else.

11
00:00:43,409 --> 00:00:44,543
What?
Like a structural trap?

12
00:00:44,610 --> 00:00:46,778
Take a look.
You tell me.

13
00:00:46,845 --> 00:00:48,180
Hey.

14
00:00:59,258 --> 00:01:00,392
What you got?

15
00:01:00,460 --> 00:01:01,560
Travis, look at this.

16
00:01:01,627 --> 00:01:04,162
We tapped
into some rocky sediment.

17
00:01:04,230 --> 00:01:05,430
It's causing real damage.

18
00:01:05,498 --> 00:01:07,265
This is
volcanic material.

19
00:01:07,333 --> 00:01:09,901
Nothing in our geologic
survey shows this.

20
00:01:09,969 --> 00:01:11,636
[Gas hissing]
methane!

21
00:01:11,704 --> 00:01:13,538
Hey, methane!

22
00:01:16,942 --> 00:01:18,143
Bill! Bill!

23
00:01:18,211 --> 00:01:19,811
[Alarm sounding]
Bill! Bill! Bill!

24
00:01:19,878 --> 00:01:21,480
Buddy, can you hear me?

25
00:01:21,547 --> 00:01:22,880
Can you hear me, huh?

26
00:01:22,948 --> 00:01:24,182
Hey, is he breathing?

27
00:01:24,250 --> 00:01:25,650
No, no!

28
00:01:25,718 --> 00:01:28,886
All right,
start the CPR!

29
00:01:28,954 --> 00:01:30,989
All right,
1, 2, 3, 4...

30
00:01:33,993 --> 00:01:34,959
Come on, Bill.

31
00:01:41,767 --> 00:01:43,435
Live bit!

32
00:01:45,605 --> 00:01:47,739
Let's go!
[Gasping]

33
00:01:47,806 --> 00:01:49,207
We got a kicker!

34
00:01:49,275 --> 00:01:50,509
There's a plume
outside the radius!

35
00:01:50,576 --> 00:01:52,544
We don't have much time!

36
00:01:52,612 --> 00:01:54,912
Hold her!
Hold her steady!

37
00:01:56,249 --> 00:01:58,950
We're under-balanced!

38
00:01:59,018 --> 00:02:01,953
[Gurgling]

39
00:02:03,822 --> 00:02:04,956
Clegg:
I'll throw the chain!

40
00:02:05,024 --> 00:02:07,325
Go!

41
00:02:07,393 --> 00:02:08,593
Careful, uncle!

42
00:02:11,297 --> 00:02:12,397
Whoa!
Aah!

43
00:02:12,465 --> 00:02:14,366
Hey!
[Screaming]

44
00:02:14,433 --> 00:02:16,501
Uncle Clegg!

45
00:02:16,569 --> 00:02:17,502
Uncle Clegg, you okay?

46
00:02:17,570 --> 00:02:18,970
What just happened?

47
00:02:20,540 --> 00:02:23,508
I think we just spiked
a volcano.

48
00:02:35,988 --> 00:02:38,623
[Thunder]

49
00:02:59,178 --> 00:03:01,946
[Thunder]

50
00:03:08,487 --> 00:03:11,590
[Thunder]

51
00:03:16,795 --> 00:03:19,364
Mr. Winters,
it's Colonel Chadwick.

52
00:03:19,432 --> 00:03:21,266
Listen,
I know Petro-Cal

53
00:03:21,334 --> 00:03:23,702
sent Travis Verdon
out to your rig.

54
00:03:23,769 --> 00:03:25,503
Yes, sir.

55
00:03:27,005 --> 00:03:29,474
This storm is building
too fast for my comfort.

56
00:03:29,542 --> 00:03:31,676
It's gonna impact
your rig in less
than an hour.

57
00:03:31,744 --> 00:03:34,346
Now, I have a NOAA vessel
in the area.

58
00:03:34,413 --> 00:03:35,980
I'd very much
like my science team

59
00:03:36,048 --> 00:03:36,848
to come
and check it out.

60
00:03:36,915 --> 00:03:39,384
Your liaison
is Dr. Jenna Sparks.

61
00:03:39,452 --> 00:03:41,253
Please see that she's
well looked after.

62
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:42,754
Of course, sir.

63
00:03:42,821 --> 00:03:45,890
We will offer her
every accommodation possible.

64
00:03:45,958 --> 00:03:47,359
Thank you, Winters.

65
00:03:47,426 --> 00:03:48,893
Look,
I know it's not easy

66
00:03:48,961 --> 00:03:50,928
having me looking
over your shoulder.

67
00:03:50,996 --> 00:03:53,431
Just try to
remember we're all
on the same side here.

68
00:03:53,499 --> 00:03:55,833
Thank you, sir.

69
00:03:59,372 --> 00:04:00,872
This must be
a hell of a storm

70
00:04:00,939 --> 00:04:03,541
if sending the big boss in
isn't enough.

71
00:04:03,609 --> 00:04:05,277
What do you mean?

72
00:04:05,344 --> 00:04:07,145
Well, Chadwick
wants to send in

73
00:04:07,212 --> 00:04:09,481
a specialist group
from NOAA.

74
00:04:09,548 --> 00:04:12,216
That's bigger
than normal.

75
00:04:12,285 --> 00:04:13,851
Yeah.

76
00:04:15,354 --> 00:04:16,788
I guess we'll see.

77
00:04:20,993 --> 00:04:22,761
[Thunder]

78
00:04:30,269 --> 00:04:32,704
You know, the nano-material
is showing real promise

79
00:04:32,772 --> 00:04:35,039
breaking up
extreme storm patterns.

80
00:04:35,107 --> 00:04:37,575
Yeah, and this, uh,
silver iodide research, too.

81
00:04:37,643 --> 00:04:38,710
It's gonna play a major role

82
00:04:38,778 --> 00:04:40,645
in preventing
catastrophic storms.

83
00:04:40,713 --> 00:04:42,347
You know what I'm picturing?
Huh?

84
00:04:42,415 --> 00:04:44,882
Cover of science news.

85
00:04:44,950 --> 00:04:45,983
[Laughs]

86
00:04:46,051 --> 00:04:47,652
Oh, I can see
the headline already.

87
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:48,653
"The Storm Killers."

88
00:04:48,721 --> 00:04:50,087
[Both laughing]

89
00:04:50,155 --> 00:04:53,124
[Cell phone rings]

90
00:04:53,192 --> 00:04:54,959
[Rings]

91
00:04:55,027 --> 00:04:55,960
Hello, Colonel.

92
00:04:56,028 --> 00:04:57,929
Dr. Sparks,
my intel is showing me

93
00:04:57,996 --> 00:05:01,299
that the landsat readings
for the Wilforce-3
are off the charts.

94
00:05:01,367 --> 00:05:03,635
Uh, yeah, we're
pretty close by her.

95
00:05:03,703 --> 00:05:05,269
Would you like us
to do a physical recon?

96
00:05:05,338 --> 00:05:06,771
Chadwick:
I would.

97
00:05:06,839 --> 00:05:08,406
Also, if there's
any malfunction

98
00:05:08,474 --> 00:05:10,375
or even
any new information,

99
00:05:10,443 --> 00:05:11,443
I'd very much
like to have you report

100
00:05:11,510 --> 00:05:13,110
back to me
as soon as possible.

101
00:05:13,178 --> 00:05:18,683
And, Dr. Sparks,
the California coastline
is a natural treasure.

102
00:05:18,751 --> 00:05:22,487
I'll be damned
if Petro-Cal takes
a dump on my beaches.

103
00:05:22,555 --> 00:05:24,021
Yes, Colonel.

104
00:05:24,089 --> 00:05:26,991
Colonel Chadwick
wants us to stop
by Wilforce-3,

105
00:05:27,059 --> 00:05:28,860
check it out.
He says the temperature

106
00:05:28,927 --> 00:05:30,862
is rising way too quickly
on that rig.

107
00:05:30,929 --> 00:05:32,330
I hope we can get
our sniffers down there

108
00:05:32,398 --> 00:05:33,965
before this storm moves in.

109
00:05:34,032 --> 00:05:35,032
Yeah, me, too.

110
00:05:35,100 --> 00:05:36,601
Colonel Chadwick already
has his hands full

111
00:05:36,669 --> 00:05:38,169
with
the storm preparation.

112
00:05:38,237 --> 00:05:40,372
Yeah, he sure doesn't need
an offshore complication.

113
00:05:40,439 --> 00:05:41,406
Nope.
I'll check it out.

114
00:05:41,474 --> 00:05:42,874
All right.

115
00:05:42,941 --> 00:05:44,175
Captain Worley,
on walkie-talkie:
Dr. Sparks?

116
00:05:45,644 --> 00:05:46,811
Yes, uh, Captain Worley,

117
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:49,414
we need to change course
for Wilforce-3.

118
00:05:49,482 --> 00:05:51,883
We've got
to turn back now!

119
00:05:51,950 --> 00:05:55,119
I do not like
the looks of these skies!

120
00:05:55,187 --> 00:05:58,222
I don't like it, either,
but we have our orders.

121
00:05:58,290 --> 00:06:00,925
Yeah, well,
I've been navigating
these waters for 20 years,

122
00:06:00,993 --> 00:06:03,661
and I never seen
nothin' look like this.

123
00:06:03,729 --> 00:06:05,597
[Thunder]

124
00:06:06,732 --> 00:06:08,032
[Ship creaks]

125
00:06:08,100 --> 00:06:09,701
Captain Worley?

126
00:06:09,769 --> 00:06:11,035
It's closing fast!

127
00:06:11,103 --> 00:06:13,405
Prepare below!

128
00:06:13,472 --> 00:06:14,773
Captain Worley!

129
00:06:14,840 --> 00:06:16,441
Rough seas ahead!

130
00:06:16,509 --> 00:06:17,776
Go!

131
00:06:22,314 --> 00:06:25,884
[Crew speaking excitedly]

132
00:06:31,424 --> 00:06:33,758
Secure the hatches!

133
00:06:34,960 --> 00:06:36,294
Get below!

134
00:06:36,361 --> 00:06:37,929
Go! Go! Go!

135
00:06:37,996 --> 00:06:40,264
Go! Go!

136
00:06:51,677 --> 00:06:53,812
She's on her beam ends!

137
00:06:59,618 --> 00:07:01,285
[Shouting]

138
00:07:01,353 --> 00:07:03,955
Man overboard!

139
00:07:09,795 --> 00:07:11,796
Man overboard!

140
00:07:16,335 --> 00:07:18,035
[Vent flares]

141
00:07:18,103 --> 00:07:21,305
[Thunder]

142
00:07:21,373 --> 00:07:22,507
Winters,
can you hear me?

143
00:07:22,575 --> 00:07:24,943
What's happening?
Where are you?

144
00:07:25,010 --> 00:07:25,777
Blowout.

145
00:07:25,845 --> 00:07:27,178
Are there any wounded?

146
00:07:27,245 --> 00:07:29,347
Joe and Paul
were killed in the blast.

147
00:07:29,414 --> 00:07:30,782
Clegg is injured.

148
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:33,084
Winters:
Travis, you got to
get out of there now.

149
00:07:33,151 --> 00:07:35,620
[Alarm sounding]
[Groans]

150
00:07:35,688 --> 00:07:37,355
Travis, get out
of there now!

151
00:07:39,692 --> 00:07:42,594
We got a punch-through
with methane.

152
00:07:43,629 --> 00:07:46,130
Joe Paul and Bill Saunders
were killed.

153
00:07:46,198 --> 00:07:47,465
Clegg?

154
00:07:47,533 --> 00:07:48,566
He's wounded.

155
00:07:48,634 --> 00:07:50,401
I don't know
his condition.

156
00:07:50,469 --> 00:07:52,069
Are we out
of alignment?

157
00:07:52,137 --> 00:07:55,607
We got 25 at zero
and 50 at 100,000 psi.

158
00:07:55,674 --> 00:07:58,109
That's enough pressure
to cut through diamonds.

159
00:07:58,176 --> 00:08:00,845
We got to enact
the blowout preventer.

160
00:08:00,913 --> 00:08:02,680
It'll take some time
to disconnect
from a mile of pipeline.

161
00:08:02,748 --> 00:08:04,382
That storm's gonna be here
in less than an hour.

162
00:08:04,449 --> 00:08:06,417
How long do you need?

163
00:08:06,485 --> 00:08:07,418
It'll be close.

164
00:08:07,486 --> 00:08:08,853
And in the meantime,

165
00:08:08,921 --> 00:08:10,989
we're dumping drilling
fluid in methane?

166
00:08:11,056 --> 00:08:11,856
Okay.

167
00:08:11,924 --> 00:08:13,892
Okay,
reroute the fluids

168
00:08:13,959 --> 00:08:15,560
and put an end
to that methane leak.

169
00:08:15,628 --> 00:08:17,395
I don't want
any more men killed.

170
00:08:17,462 --> 00:08:18,997
Yes, sir.

171
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:22,700
[Groans]

172
00:08:22,768 --> 00:08:24,301
Secure the equipment!

173
00:08:24,369 --> 00:08:25,803
What's your reading?

174
00:08:25,871 --> 00:08:27,204
Well, the temperature
differential

175
00:08:27,272 --> 00:08:30,241
shot from 65 to 129
in a couple of hours.

176
00:08:30,308 --> 00:08:32,143
They must have broken
into molten lava.

177
00:08:32,210 --> 00:08:33,645
Yeah, if my reading's
correct,

178
00:08:33,712 --> 00:08:35,379
that thing's a volcano.

179
00:08:36,582 --> 00:08:38,516
[Thunder]

180
00:08:38,584 --> 00:08:40,184
[Hatch slams open]

181
00:08:46,425 --> 00:08:47,725
Unh!

182
00:08:48,961 --> 00:08:50,895
Wilforce-3
is in serious trouble.

183
00:08:50,963 --> 00:08:52,897
They need to know
what they're sitting on.

184
00:08:55,233 --> 00:08:57,501
Sea rover to Wilforce-3,
come in please!

185
00:08:57,570 --> 00:08:58,603
[Static]

186
00:08:58,671 --> 00:09:00,038
Wilforce-3, come in!

187
00:09:00,105 --> 00:09:01,472
Radio operator:
Wilforce-3 to Sea Rover.

188
00:09:01,540 --> 00:09:02,674
State your communication.

189
00:09:02,741 --> 00:09:04,141
This is Dr. Jenna Sparks.

190
00:09:04,209 --> 00:09:06,711
I'm a research
meteorologist investigating

191
00:09:06,779 --> 00:09:08,512
the atmospheric condition
around the rig.

192
00:09:08,581 --> 00:09:11,616
I need to speak with
your manager immediately!

193
00:09:11,684 --> 00:09:15,086
Radio operator:
let me connect you
to rig manager Winters.

194
00:09:15,153 --> 00:09:16,220
Operator?

195
00:09:16,288 --> 00:09:17,622
[Static]

196
00:09:17,690 --> 00:09:19,390
Wilforce-3,
come in please.

197
00:09:19,458 --> 00:09:21,425
[Clegg groaning]

198
00:09:22,962 --> 00:09:25,296
Wilforce-3,
please, come in!

199
00:09:25,363 --> 00:09:27,131
[Static]

200
00:09:27,199 --> 00:09:28,199
[Thud]
Unh!

201
00:09:31,070 --> 00:09:33,638
What's happening down there?

202
00:09:33,706 --> 00:09:35,372
We hit some kind
of molten deposit.

203
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:38,109
I'm worried about
the stability of this rig.

204
00:09:39,244 --> 00:09:40,244
Can you move?

205
00:09:40,312 --> 00:09:42,647
Yeah. Yeah,
all right, all right.

206
00:09:42,715 --> 00:09:44,015
Listen, listen.

207
00:09:44,083 --> 00:09:46,751
The generator turbines
are still on.

208
00:09:46,819 --> 00:09:49,186
I know. That methane
is still leaking.

209
00:09:49,254 --> 00:09:52,223
It should
deactivate automatically.

210
00:09:52,290 --> 00:09:54,659
No, the electricians
are troubleshooting.

211
00:09:54,727 --> 00:09:57,428
They turned off
auto shutdown.

212
00:09:57,496 --> 00:09:59,631
I know, but you got
to move a little faster.

213
00:09:59,698 --> 00:10:00,865
Can you?

214
00:10:00,933 --> 00:10:02,500
'Cause if that methane
catches a spark,

215
00:10:02,567 --> 00:10:04,335
we're like toast.

216
00:10:04,402 --> 00:10:05,737
Come on.
All right.

217
00:10:05,804 --> 00:10:07,805
All right, let's go.
[Groans]

218
00:10:14,713 --> 00:10:15,880
There she is.

219
00:10:15,948 --> 00:10:17,782
Warm water,
moist air.

220
00:10:17,850 --> 00:10:19,316
It's the devil's
playground.

221
00:10:19,384 --> 00:10:21,119
It's massive.

222
00:10:21,186 --> 00:10:24,321
We've, uh, got
less than half an hour
to reach that rig.

223
00:10:24,389 --> 00:10:26,057
We got to go now!

224
00:10:32,665 --> 00:10:35,133
[Engines whining]

225
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:37,769
Come on, come on,
come on.

226
00:10:37,836 --> 00:10:39,470
Lean on me.

227
00:10:39,538 --> 00:10:40,805
The generators.

228
00:10:40,873 --> 00:10:42,907
This way.
Just a little further.

229
00:10:42,975 --> 00:10:44,976
The smell, the smell.

230
00:10:45,044 --> 00:10:46,443
We're almost there.

231
00:10:46,511 --> 00:10:48,680
Come on, come on!

232
00:10:48,747 --> 00:10:50,114
[Explosion]

233
00:10:57,990 --> 00:11:00,324
Uncle...
Uncle Clegg!

234
00:11:00,392 --> 00:11:01,358
Uncle Clegg!

235
00:11:01,426 --> 00:11:02,894
Are you okay?

236
00:11:02,961 --> 00:11:06,064
Hey,
can you hear me?

237
00:11:06,131 --> 00:11:07,899
Come on.

238
00:11:07,966 --> 00:11:10,401
Come on,
get up, get up.

239
00:11:10,468 --> 00:11:11,969
Get up.

240
00:11:15,808 --> 00:11:17,408
[Explosion]

241
00:11:22,848 --> 00:11:23,815
Aah!

242
00:11:23,882 --> 00:11:25,683
What was that?

243
00:11:25,751 --> 00:11:26,884
I don't know!

244
00:11:26,952 --> 00:11:28,119
[Grunts]

245
00:11:29,988 --> 00:11:31,655
Rotor stall!

246
00:11:31,724 --> 00:11:33,390
Going into a nosedive!

247
00:11:33,458 --> 00:11:34,792
Pull up!

248
00:11:34,860 --> 00:11:36,660
[Both straining]

249
00:11:36,729 --> 00:11:39,230
Turbulence!
Come on!

250
00:11:45,804 --> 00:11:47,638
Come on!
We need to pull up!

251
00:11:47,706 --> 00:11:49,673
Almost! [Grunts]

252
00:11:49,742 --> 00:11:51,843
Almost got it!

253
00:11:54,512 --> 00:11:57,014
[Relieved sigh]

254
00:12:00,219 --> 00:12:04,255
All right, nice flying.

255
00:12:09,361 --> 00:12:10,728
We've lost
our generators.

256
00:12:10,796 --> 00:12:12,130
We're on fire.

257
00:12:12,197 --> 00:12:14,531
We got to evacuate now
before that storm comes in.

258
00:12:14,599 --> 00:12:16,934
Yes, sir.
Mobilize the lifeboats,

259
00:12:17,002 --> 00:12:19,103
prepare for evacuation.

260
00:12:24,743 --> 00:12:27,145
This man
needs help now!

261
00:12:27,212 --> 00:12:29,046
All right, I'm a medic.
We'll get him to the chopper.

262
00:12:29,114 --> 00:12:31,582
What happened
to your friend?

263
00:12:31,650 --> 00:12:32,850
He's my uncle.

264
00:12:32,918 --> 00:12:34,185
It was an accident
in the pump room.

265
00:12:34,253 --> 00:12:36,921
Well, Dr. Cavanaugh
will take good care of him.

266
00:12:36,989 --> 00:12:39,456
I'm Dr. Jenna Sparks
from the NOAA.

267
00:12:39,524 --> 00:12:41,959
I need to speak
to your rig manager now.

268
00:12:42,027 --> 00:12:43,527
Follow me!

269
00:12:43,595 --> 00:12:45,263
[Thunder]

270
00:12:45,330 --> 00:12:46,831
[Alarm blaring]
I'm Travis Verdon.

271
00:12:46,899 --> 00:12:48,866
I'm here at request
of Colonel Chadwick.

272
00:12:48,934 --> 00:12:50,768
It's been pretty bad
out here today.

273
00:12:50,836 --> 00:12:51,836
What happened?

274
00:12:51,904 --> 00:12:53,604
We hit a pocket
of molten lava.

275
00:12:53,672 --> 00:12:56,808
The heat from that rupture
is creating an event.

276
00:12:56,875 --> 00:12:58,042
What kind of event?

277
00:12:58,110 --> 00:12:59,643
The water is superheating

278
00:12:59,711 --> 00:13:02,379
making the surrounding air
highly unstable.

279
00:13:02,447 --> 00:13:05,683
What does this mean
to the rig?

280
00:13:05,750 --> 00:13:09,153
Can you handle a storm
with the power
of five katrinas?

281
00:13:09,221 --> 00:13:11,289
1,000 miles
per hour winds?

282
00:13:11,356 --> 00:13:12,690
I mean,
how can that be?

283
00:13:12,757 --> 00:13:14,558
We're not in the tropics.

284
00:13:14,626 --> 00:13:16,694
The warm water is
creating cyclone conditions.

285
00:13:16,761 --> 00:13:19,396
It's changing everything
we know about the weather.

286
00:13:24,036 --> 00:13:25,336
Travis.

287
00:13:25,403 --> 00:13:26,904
Rowell: What happened
in the pump room?

288
00:13:26,972 --> 00:13:28,572
Joe and Bill were
killed in the blast.

289
00:13:28,640 --> 00:13:29,807
My uncle
was badly wounded.

290
00:13:29,875 --> 00:13:31,843
I got him
prepped for evac.

291
00:13:31,910 --> 00:13:33,510
I'm sorry to hear that.

292
00:13:33,578 --> 00:13:35,947
What exactly
happened in there?

293
00:13:36,014 --> 00:13:37,414
We hit a pocket
of magma,

294
00:13:37,482 --> 00:13:39,483
a lava blast
that came up through
the bore hole.

295
00:13:39,551 --> 00:13:42,353
Mr. Winters, Colonel Chadwick
sent me to investigate.

296
00:13:42,420 --> 00:13:43,955
I'm an atmospheric specialist.

297
00:13:44,022 --> 00:13:47,791
The warm water is creating
the first cyclone in California.

298
00:13:47,860 --> 00:13:49,327
A cyclone?

299
00:13:49,394 --> 00:13:51,028
It's going to unleash
a chain of events

300
00:13:51,096 --> 00:13:53,630
that's going to threaten
the entire West Coast.

301
00:13:53,698 --> 00:13:55,333
What kind of events?

302
00:13:55,400 --> 00:13:57,434
It's going to be a storm
like you've never seen before.

303
00:13:57,502 --> 00:14:01,438
It's what we call
a super cyclone.

304
00:14:01,506 --> 00:14:04,375
Sir, I got over
100 company men
on this rig.

305
00:14:04,442 --> 00:14:06,443
This storm will impact this rig
in a matter of minutes.

306
00:14:06,511 --> 00:14:07,611
Evacuate

307
00:14:07,679 --> 00:14:09,513
all non-essential
personnel immediately.

308
00:14:09,581 --> 00:14:11,315
I don't want anyone
left on this rig

309
00:14:11,383 --> 00:14:12,516
other than
the hazard team.

310
00:14:12,584 --> 00:14:14,518
I'm on it.

311
00:14:14,586 --> 00:14:16,487
Travis, we got to get
your uncle out of here.

312
00:14:16,554 --> 00:14:18,022
He's in good hands.
I'm staying.

313
00:14:18,090 --> 00:14:19,290
What do you need me
to do to help?

314
00:14:19,358 --> 00:14:20,624
Travis, I know
that you're here to help,

315
00:14:20,692 --> 00:14:23,560
but I am still
the safety officer on this rig.

316
00:14:23,628 --> 00:14:24,896
Now, this is my call.

317
00:14:24,963 --> 00:14:26,330
I am ordering you
to leave.

318
00:14:26,398 --> 00:14:28,465
Listen,
I'm a structural
engineer, Gary.

319
00:14:28,533 --> 00:14:29,733
Let me help you.

320
00:14:29,801 --> 00:14:31,168
That's exactly why.

321
00:14:31,236 --> 00:14:32,469
I can't think
of anyone better

322
00:14:32,537 --> 00:14:34,372
to coordinate
the crisis effort.

323
00:14:34,439 --> 00:14:39,743
Now, Colonel Chadwick
is a soldier, not an oil man.

324
00:14:39,811 --> 00:14:41,345
Believe me,
you'd do much better

325
00:14:41,413 --> 00:14:43,381
for me off this rig
than on it.

326
00:14:43,448 --> 00:14:44,982
Understood.
I got your back.

327
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:47,518
Well, if we're gonna
get off this rig,
we need to go now.

328
00:14:47,585 --> 00:14:48,519
Okay.

329
00:14:59,697 --> 00:15:01,065
How is he?

330
00:15:01,133 --> 00:15:02,266
I had to put
a tourniquet

331
00:15:02,334 --> 00:15:03,600
on his leg
to stop the bleeding.

332
00:15:03,668 --> 00:15:04,835
Can't feel my leg.

333
00:15:04,903 --> 00:15:06,337
I can do more for him
back at the Sea Rover.

334
00:15:06,405 --> 00:15:08,072
Don't let me
lose my leg!

335
00:15:08,140 --> 00:15:09,273
You're in good hands.

336
00:15:09,341 --> 00:15:10,408
You're gonna be
all right, uncle.

337
00:15:10,475 --> 00:15:12,009
Hang in there.
Come on, let's go.

338
00:15:12,077 --> 00:15:14,611
Oh, no.
[Thunder]

339
00:15:14,679 --> 00:15:17,181
We're on the leading edge
of the storm.

340
00:15:18,883 --> 00:15:20,617
We're all set back here.

341
00:15:20,685 --> 00:15:21,819
Okay, hang on tight.

342
00:15:21,886 --> 00:15:23,520
[Engines whining]

343
00:15:33,665 --> 00:15:37,201
Sparks, if you are not here
in five minutes,

344
00:15:37,269 --> 00:15:38,535
I am leavin'!

345
00:15:38,603 --> 00:15:40,338
I have lost crew,
and I swear to god,

346
00:15:40,405 --> 00:15:41,705
I am not gonna lose
any more.

347
00:15:41,773 --> 00:15:43,207
Do you hear me?

348
00:15:43,275 --> 00:15:45,742
Worley,
don't go anywhere!

349
00:15:45,810 --> 00:15:47,544
We're on our way!

350
00:15:47,612 --> 00:15:48,712
[Thunder]

351
00:15:53,185 --> 00:15:55,152
[Gasping and straining]

352
00:16:01,626 --> 00:16:03,794
Come on.

353
00:16:17,642 --> 00:16:18,976
I'll meet you
on the nav bridge.

354
00:16:19,044 --> 00:16:20,344
All right.

355
00:16:20,412 --> 00:16:22,146
Hey, Worley, we got
a wounded man here.

356
00:16:22,214 --> 00:16:23,780
I'll need to stitch him up.

357
00:16:23,848 --> 00:16:25,016
Take him
to the galley.

358
00:16:25,083 --> 00:16:27,485
Use the big steel
counter.

359
00:16:27,552 --> 00:16:29,320
Make it quick.
Come on, come on!

360
00:16:34,026 --> 00:16:35,759
All right,
here we go.

361
00:16:35,827 --> 00:16:37,428
Easy.

362
00:16:37,496 --> 00:16:39,063
All right, get him up
on the table there.

363
00:16:39,131 --> 00:16:40,531
Feet down at the end.

364
00:16:40,598 --> 00:16:41,899
Get up here.

365
00:16:45,170 --> 00:16:47,505
Get some towels here.
Watch your head there, buddy.

366
00:16:47,572 --> 00:16:49,140
Okay.

367
00:16:50,308 --> 00:16:51,675
You okay?

368
00:16:51,743 --> 00:16:52,809
Oh, the rig.

369
00:16:52,877 --> 00:16:54,111
I'm gonna wash up
and grab my bag.

370
00:16:54,179 --> 00:16:55,179
Okay.
The rig?

371
00:16:55,247 --> 00:16:56,680
I know.

372
00:16:56,748 --> 00:17:00,184
I tried to stay,
but Gary ordered me off.

373
00:17:00,252 --> 00:17:02,953
They're my family.

374
00:17:03,021 --> 00:17:05,989
I spent my whole life
on the rig,

375
00:17:06,058 --> 00:17:07,824
my whole life.

376
00:17:07,892 --> 00:17:10,194
I know, I know.

377
00:17:10,262 --> 00:17:13,064
I promise you,
I'm gonna get the men out.

378
00:17:13,131 --> 00:17:15,199
I promise you that,
uncle.

379
00:17:15,267 --> 00:17:18,469
Look at me.
Look at me--filthy.

380
00:17:18,537 --> 00:17:23,340
My whole life,
my whole life...

381
00:17:23,408 --> 00:17:28,546
Dirty--
dirty, dangerous job, huh?

382
00:17:28,613 --> 00:17:29,880
You...

383
00:17:29,948 --> 00:17:31,248
Hey.

384
00:17:31,316 --> 00:17:33,184
College...

385
00:17:34,519 --> 00:17:36,153
clean shirt,
right?

386
00:17:36,221 --> 00:17:38,255
Clean shirt.

387
00:17:38,323 --> 00:17:40,724
Aw, I'm so proud of you.

388
00:17:40,792 --> 00:17:42,293
I'm proud of you.

389
00:17:42,360 --> 00:17:43,894
Thanks, uncle Clegg.

390
00:17:43,962 --> 00:17:45,696
I'm proud of you.

391
00:17:45,763 --> 00:17:47,431
You're
gonna be all right.

392
00:17:50,001 --> 00:17:52,136
Hey,
anything I can do?

393
00:17:52,204 --> 00:17:54,738
Yeah, uh, Travis,
um, tell you what,

394
00:17:54,806 --> 00:17:56,840
why don't you wait up
on the nav bridge, okay?

395
00:17:56,908 --> 00:17:58,742
Okay, all right.

396
00:17:58,810 --> 00:18:00,911
You gonna be all right?

397
00:18:00,979 --> 00:18:02,446
Yeah, sure.

398
00:18:02,514 --> 00:18:05,649
I'm right out here,
all right?

399
00:18:05,717 --> 00:18:07,284
Right, right.

400
00:18:07,352 --> 00:18:08,919
I'll take good care
of him, don't worry.

401
00:18:08,987 --> 00:18:09,953
Travis:
All right.

402
00:18:13,024 --> 00:18:16,927
[Thunder]

403
00:18:16,995 --> 00:18:19,130
Can't we go any faster?

404
00:18:19,197 --> 00:18:21,265
No, we missed
our chance to move fast.

405
00:18:21,333 --> 00:18:23,601
Now it's a chess game.

406
00:18:23,668 --> 00:18:25,802
You see them big waves
out there?

407
00:18:25,870 --> 00:18:28,672
The worse thing can happen
is we start to run

408
00:18:28,740 --> 00:18:30,974
down the face
of one of them big ones.

409
00:18:31,042 --> 00:18:32,543
Are they gonna
swamp us?

410
00:18:32,611 --> 00:18:36,280
Hell, no,
not if I can help it.

411
00:18:48,026 --> 00:18:50,528
[Wind howling]

412
00:18:52,197 --> 00:18:53,631
How's your uncle?

413
00:18:53,698 --> 00:18:56,467
Doctor C's
still working on him.

414
00:18:56,535 --> 00:18:58,269
Where's the storm?

415
00:18:58,336 --> 00:18:59,803
I'm sorry, Travis.

416
00:18:59,871 --> 00:19:02,640
The storm's hitting
Wilforce-3 right now.

417
00:19:02,707 --> 00:19:04,007
What?

418
00:19:17,055 --> 00:19:19,823
Scramble the rescue nets!

419
00:19:19,891 --> 00:19:21,725
Do you see him?

420
00:19:23,995 --> 00:19:25,062
Get the ladders now!

421
00:19:25,129 --> 00:19:27,798
Over there!
Over there!

422
00:19:31,536 --> 00:19:32,936
Winters: Activate
the transmitters!

423
00:19:33,004 --> 00:19:34,505
Man overboard!

424
00:19:34,573 --> 00:19:37,675
[Water boiling]

425
00:19:37,742 --> 00:19:39,410
Aah!

426
00:19:39,477 --> 00:19:41,144
Man overboard!

427
00:19:41,213 --> 00:19:44,348
Samuels, pull!
Quick turn! Quick turn!

428
00:19:44,416 --> 00:19:46,817
[Men screaming]

429
00:19:48,986 --> 00:19:51,154
There's the strobe!

430
00:19:51,223 --> 00:19:53,056
[Screaming]

431
00:19:56,394 --> 00:19:58,495
Help!

432
00:20:00,432 --> 00:20:01,898
[Screaming]

433
00:20:03,801 --> 00:20:04,801
No!

434
00:20:08,139 --> 00:20:09,072
No!

435
00:20:10,408 --> 00:20:12,243
Starboard side, now!

436
00:20:12,310 --> 00:20:13,810
[Men shouting]

437
00:20:14,912 --> 00:20:17,514
The lifeboats
are failing.

438
00:20:17,582 --> 00:20:20,484
Pull back!
Abandon
the lifeboats!

439
00:20:26,258 --> 00:20:28,659
Come back!

440
00:20:28,727 --> 00:20:30,394
God! No!

441
00:20:35,433 --> 00:20:36,867
[Screaming]

442
00:20:36,934 --> 00:20:38,902
God, they're
boiling alive.

443
00:20:38,970 --> 00:20:40,537
Bring them back!

444
00:20:44,008 --> 00:20:45,075
Stop the evac!

445
00:20:45,143 --> 00:20:46,209
Stop the evac!

446
00:20:46,278 --> 00:20:47,645
It's a bloodbath
out there!

447
00:20:51,483 --> 00:20:52,816
Where are
the rescue helicopters?

448
00:20:52,884 --> 00:20:54,518
Even if they got
the distress call,

449
00:20:54,586 --> 00:20:55,719
the storm's
gotten too bad.

450
00:20:55,787 --> 00:20:57,288
The only thing
we can do now

451
00:20:57,355 --> 00:20:59,089
is try to plug
the punch-through.

452
00:20:59,157 --> 00:21:01,124
Okay, okay,
shunt the spacers

453
00:21:01,192 --> 00:21:03,126
and bypass
the pressure gauges.

454
00:21:03,194 --> 00:21:05,128
That's our
only warning system!

455
00:21:05,196 --> 00:21:07,130
We've got no choice!

456
00:21:15,072 --> 00:21:17,408
[Thunder]

457
00:21:17,475 --> 00:21:20,110
[Wind howling]

458
00:21:46,003 --> 00:21:47,671
Oh.

459
00:22:12,764 --> 00:22:14,631
Here you go, buddy.

460
00:22:28,946 --> 00:22:31,648
Hey, doc,
how's my uncle doing?

461
00:22:31,716 --> 00:22:33,684
Well, I stitched him up.

462
00:22:33,752 --> 00:22:35,519
I did the best I could.

463
00:22:35,587 --> 00:22:37,187
Will he get
to keep his leg?

464
00:22:37,255 --> 00:22:41,224
I'll be happier
when we get him
to a hospital.

465
00:22:41,292 --> 00:22:43,994
Oh, man, I have never
seen anything like this.

466
00:22:44,061 --> 00:22:46,597
I got to get those men
off that rig.

467
00:22:46,664 --> 00:22:48,899
We're racing
ahead of the storm,

468
00:22:48,966 --> 00:22:51,067
but it's gonna hit landfall
at point conception

469
00:22:51,135 --> 00:22:52,269
in less than an hour.

470
00:22:55,339 --> 00:22:56,874
Here she comes!

471
00:22:57,742 --> 00:22:59,276
Brace yourselves!

472
00:23:01,446 --> 00:23:02,946
Oh!

473
00:23:15,092 --> 00:23:16,126
[Grunts]

474
00:23:30,742 --> 00:23:32,810
[Groans]

475
00:23:32,877 --> 00:23:33,844
Oh!

476
00:23:42,520 --> 00:23:44,287
We're breaking free.

477
00:23:45,857 --> 00:23:49,593
This storm,
it's moving way too fast.

478
00:23:49,661 --> 00:23:51,061
[Thunder]

479
00:23:51,128 --> 00:23:54,164
Did that oil rig cause
this whole damn thing?

480
00:23:57,201 --> 00:23:59,536
There's
a super cyclone coming.

481
00:23:59,604 --> 00:24:01,839
Millions of people
are gonna die.

482
00:24:07,545 --> 00:24:09,546
We're headed south.
We broke free.

483
00:24:09,614 --> 00:24:11,482
Well,
that's temporary.

484
00:24:11,549 --> 00:24:12,683
It's only
a matter of hours

485
00:24:12,750 --> 00:24:14,918
before it slams
greater Los Angeles.

486
00:24:14,986 --> 00:24:16,386
Reporter: The national
weather service has issued

487
00:24:16,454 --> 00:24:17,688
a severe
Pacific storm warning.

488
00:24:17,755 --> 00:24:18,922
Prepare for damaging winds,

489
00:24:18,990 --> 00:24:20,958
storm surges,
and flash flooding.

490
00:24:21,025 --> 00:24:25,562
There's no way
for them to prepare
for a storm of this size.

491
00:24:25,630 --> 00:24:27,865
We've got to stop it.

492
00:24:29,233 --> 00:24:31,368
[Thunder]

493
00:24:34,205 --> 00:24:37,307
We're just ahead of her.

494
00:24:37,375 --> 00:24:38,775
Not for long.

495
00:24:38,843 --> 00:24:41,244
It's gonna be on us
in about two hours.

496
00:24:43,381 --> 00:24:44,781
Right up there.

497
00:24:46,183 --> 00:24:47,718
There's the Marina.

498
00:24:47,785 --> 00:24:49,419
We may be able to use

499
00:24:49,487 --> 00:24:53,256
my nanotechnology research
to stop the storm.

500
00:25:04,836 --> 00:25:07,370
[Fire dispatcher
speaking on radio]

501
00:25:08,706 --> 00:25:10,473
Cavanaugh: Get this man
to a hospital!

502
00:25:10,542 --> 00:25:12,509
Hey, you okay, uncle, huh?

503
00:25:12,577 --> 00:25:14,177
Go, go.

504
00:25:14,245 --> 00:25:15,178
I'm not gonna leave you.

505
00:25:15,246 --> 00:25:16,847
The best thing
you can do for me

506
00:25:16,915 --> 00:25:18,682
is get our brothers
off that rig.

507
00:25:19,751 --> 00:25:21,484
I want to make sure
you're gonna be okay.

508
00:25:21,553 --> 00:25:23,219
If not you, then who?

509
00:25:25,723 --> 00:25:27,457
All right.

510
00:25:27,525 --> 00:25:29,392
You hang in there,
you hear me?

511
00:25:29,460 --> 00:25:30,627
You, too.
All right.

512
00:25:30,695 --> 00:25:32,062
All right, go ahead.

513
00:25:32,129 --> 00:25:33,730
Thanks for saving
my life, doc.

514
00:25:33,798 --> 00:25:35,165
Hey, I expect to see
you walking on that

515
00:25:35,232 --> 00:25:37,801
next time I see you,
all right?

516
00:25:37,869 --> 00:25:38,969
Let's get
off this boat.

517
00:25:39,037 --> 00:25:40,704
We got
to get moving.

518
00:25:43,340 --> 00:25:45,141
[Thunder]

519
00:26:00,324 --> 00:26:02,158
[Computers beeping]

520
00:26:09,266 --> 00:26:12,302
I can't reach
the Petro-Cal headquarters.

521
00:26:12,369 --> 00:26:14,805
All communication
and data lines are out.

522
00:26:14,872 --> 00:26:16,873
I'm sorry, Travis,

523
00:26:16,941 --> 00:26:19,776
but the Wilforce-3,
it's in the eye
of the storm now.

524
00:26:19,844 --> 00:26:22,245
Look, I got to help
the men on the rig.

525
00:26:22,313 --> 00:26:24,014
Travis, listen to me,
listen to me.

526
00:26:24,082 --> 00:26:26,049
The leading edge
of the super cyclone

527
00:26:26,117 --> 00:26:28,085
has already made landfall
at point conception.

528
00:26:28,152 --> 00:26:31,588
It's taken out power grids,
communication capabilities,

529
00:26:31,656 --> 00:26:33,156
transportation arteries.

530
00:26:33,224 --> 00:26:36,994
And, I mean, that's
just the tip of the iceberg.

531
00:26:37,061 --> 00:26:39,496
I mean, once the full force
of this storm hits

532
00:26:39,563 --> 00:26:41,632
the major
population centers....

533
00:26:41,699 --> 00:26:43,700
Look, you have
to take me back.

