too much, Annabel.

1065
00:52:22,405 --> 00:52:23,338
You have to eat.

1066
00:52:23,406 --> 00:52:24,373
Just take these
at least.

1067
00:52:24,440 --> 00:52:25,740
All right.
Thank you.

1068
00:52:25,808 --> 00:52:27,108
Thank you.

1069
00:52:27,177 --> 00:52:28,843
Well, it looks like the storm's
giving us a break.

1070
00:52:28,911 --> 00:52:29,978
We should go.

1071
00:52:30,046 --> 00:52:31,547
Yeah, we better
take advantage of it.

1072
00:52:31,614 --> 00:52:33,348
Be safe.

1073
00:52:33,416 --> 00:52:35,016
Thank you again.

1074
00:53:00,243 --> 00:53:01,543
[Horns honk]

1075
00:53:01,611 --> 00:53:03,212
Reporter:
...emergency warning system.

1076
00:53:03,279 --> 00:53:04,713
Widespread flooding
has inundated

1077
00:53:04,780 --> 00:53:08,149
portions of the 405,
110, 101 and 5 freeways,

1078
00:53:08,218 --> 00:53:09,818
forcing major road closures.

1079
00:53:09,885 --> 00:53:11,587
Do not drive
into flooded areas

1080
00:53:11,654 --> 00:53:13,755
or go around barricades.

1081
00:53:13,823 --> 00:53:17,392
Storm ocean surge impact level
has reached 43 feet.

1082
00:53:17,460 --> 00:53:19,194
If you are in the path
of the storm,

1083
00:53:19,262 --> 00:53:21,029
take cover immediately.

1084
00:53:24,934 --> 00:53:27,102
What's the status
on the evacuation?

1085
00:53:27,169 --> 00:53:28,670
The situation
is not good, sir.

1086
00:53:28,738 --> 00:53:31,573
Major arteries
and freeways are
completely blocked.

1087
00:53:31,641 --> 00:53:33,275
What about
public transportation?

1088
00:53:33,343 --> 00:53:35,377
Caltrans is reporting
that the high winds

1089
00:53:35,445 --> 00:53:37,646
have knocked
three trains off the tracks.

1090
00:53:37,714 --> 00:53:39,481
People able
to get out of the city?

1091
00:53:39,549 --> 00:53:44,185
Sir, the 405, 110, and 10
are parking lots.

1092
00:53:44,254 --> 00:53:46,154
People are getting
out of their cars and running.

1093
00:53:46,222 --> 00:53:47,389
Running to where?

1094
00:53:47,457 --> 00:53:49,291
There's nowhere
to run to, sir.

1095
00:53:49,359 --> 00:53:50,592
What about
emergency services?

1096
00:53:50,660 --> 00:53:52,227
Hospitals are overwhelmed.

1097
00:53:52,295 --> 00:53:54,363
Fires are burning
out of control.

1098
00:53:54,430 --> 00:53:55,864
We have
over 10 million people

1099
00:53:55,931 --> 00:53:58,400
without power
and more every second.

1100
00:53:58,468 --> 00:53:59,868
What's the governor
saying about all this?

1101
00:53:59,935 --> 00:54:01,570
Sir, he's
mobilizing resources,

1102
00:54:01,638 --> 00:54:04,205
but they just can't get here
to help us fast enough.

1103
00:54:04,274 --> 00:54:05,540
Word on the street?

1104
00:54:05,608 --> 00:54:08,744
Sir, it's panic.

1105
00:54:08,811 --> 00:54:11,246
People are scared,
confused,

1106
00:54:11,314 --> 00:54:13,181
and most of them armed.

1107
00:54:13,249 --> 00:54:14,883
It's not
a good combination.

1108
00:54:30,733 --> 00:54:34,869
Sir, the president
just declared
a state of emergency.

1109
00:54:34,937 --> 00:54:37,806
There are resources
being mobilized,

1110
00:54:37,873 --> 00:54:41,142
but we're not gonna
get any help until
the storm is over.

1111
00:54:41,210 --> 00:54:44,379
Over? This is
just pre-storm turbulence.

1112
00:54:44,447 --> 00:54:46,515
The storm
hasn't even hit yet!

1113
00:54:56,192 --> 00:54:57,726
How we doing on fuel?

1114
00:54:57,794 --> 00:55:00,295
We have a little less
than a half a tank.

1115
00:55:00,363 --> 00:55:01,963
I hope that's enough.

1116
00:55:02,031 --> 00:55:03,365
Better be.

1117
00:55:03,433 --> 00:55:04,466
Yeah, well,
it's gonna take longer

1118
00:55:04,534 --> 00:55:05,867
not taking the freeway.

1119
00:55:05,935 --> 00:55:07,936
Yeah, every major artery
in the city is jammed.

1120
00:55:08,003 --> 00:55:10,772
Imagine what the I-5
looks like right now.

1121
00:55:10,840 --> 00:55:11,807
Hell.

1122
00:55:11,874 --> 00:55:13,809
Oh, hey, hey!
Over here!

1123
00:55:13,876 --> 00:55:14,710
Turn on 74.

1124
00:55:14,777 --> 00:55:16,277
Hey, the national forest.

1125
00:55:16,346 --> 00:55:18,012
Yeah, it's gonna take us
out to the back end
of the base.

1126
00:55:18,080 --> 00:55:19,314
Perfect.

1127
00:55:19,382 --> 00:55:20,682
Yeah, if we have
any luck,

1128
00:55:20,750 --> 00:55:22,116
a marine patrol
might pick us up.

1129
00:55:22,184 --> 00:55:23,218
Mmm.

1130
00:55:23,285 --> 00:55:24,720
Careful!

1131
00:55:27,590 --> 00:55:29,924
I got it, I got it,
I got it!

1132
00:55:33,295 --> 00:55:36,064
What's going on
with that tree?

1133
00:55:43,973 --> 00:55:48,076
Well, looks like
it's starting to let up.

1134
00:55:48,143 --> 00:55:50,178
The road
got washed away.

1135
00:55:50,246 --> 00:55:51,713
I'll have
to go around it.

1136
00:55:51,781 --> 00:55:53,348
All right, well,
just take it careful.

1137
00:55:53,416 --> 00:55:55,149
Slow, slow.

1138
00:55:55,217 --> 00:55:57,151
Here we go.

1139
00:55:57,219 --> 00:55:59,354
Travis.
Travis, the road!

1140
00:55:59,422 --> 00:56:01,022
Back up, back up!

1141
00:56:01,090 --> 00:56:02,223
Where?

1142
00:56:05,327 --> 00:56:06,395
I can't!
I'm stuck!

1143
00:56:06,462 --> 00:56:07,562
Okay, okay,
we got to get out!

1144
00:56:07,630 --> 00:56:08,630
Stop the car!

1145
00:56:08,698 --> 00:56:09,865
All right, all right.

1146
00:56:09,932 --> 00:56:11,700
All right.
Come on, let's go!

1147
00:56:24,246 --> 00:56:25,747
Be careful!

1148
00:56:27,917 --> 00:56:28,884
This way!

1149
00:56:30,219 --> 00:56:31,920
Right over here,
guys!

1150
00:56:31,987 --> 00:56:34,022
I think we can
make it across the trees.

1151
00:56:34,089 --> 00:56:35,290
Come on.

1152
00:56:39,261 --> 00:56:40,295
Come on, hurry!

1153
00:56:40,362 --> 00:56:41,329
Grab my hand!

1154
00:56:41,397 --> 00:56:43,264
Unh!

1155
00:56:46,302 --> 00:56:47,602
Oh, my god.

1156
00:56:47,670 --> 00:56:48,703
Doc, let's go!
Come on!

1157
00:56:48,771 --> 00:56:50,238
Come on! Percy!

1158
00:56:50,306 --> 00:56:51,440
You can make it!
Come on, doc!

1159
00:56:51,507 --> 00:56:52,441
Hurry up!
The ground's
giving way!

1160
00:56:52,508 --> 00:56:53,708
Come on!

1161
00:56:53,776 --> 00:56:54,876
Doc, come on!

1162
00:56:54,944 --> 00:56:56,277
I can't reach!
I'm not gonna make it!

1163
00:56:56,345 --> 00:56:57,412
Come on, doc!

1164
00:56:57,480 --> 00:56:58,480
You can do it!
You can make it!

1165
00:56:58,548 --> 00:56:59,748
I'm not gonna make it!

1166
00:56:59,816 --> 00:57:01,115
Doc, come on!

1167
00:57:01,183 --> 00:57:02,317
Come on, doc!

1168
00:57:02,384 --> 00:57:03,752
I can't reach!
Come on!

1169
00:57:03,820 --> 00:57:05,487
Can't reach!
Doc!

1170
00:57:05,555 --> 00:57:06,688
Aah!

1171
00:57:06,756 --> 00:57:08,122
No!
No!

1172
00:57:08,190 --> 00:57:10,058
Aah!

1173
00:57:11,594 --> 00:57:12,727
Jenna!

1174
00:57:12,795 --> 00:57:14,062
He was just there!

1175
00:57:14,129 --> 00:57:15,129
Gone!

1176
00:57:15,197 --> 00:57:16,798
He just vanished!

1177
00:57:19,669 --> 00:57:23,071
Hamilton class,
this is Wilforce-3.

1178
00:57:23,138 --> 00:57:24,339
Go ahead.

1179
00:57:26,642 --> 00:57:28,443
Hamilton class,
do you copy?

1180
00:57:28,511 --> 00:57:29,911
Mayday! Mayday!

1181
00:57:29,979 --> 00:57:32,313
Radio operator:
Wilforce-3, come in.

1182
00:57:32,381 --> 00:57:34,950
Hamilton class
this is Wilforce-3

1183
00:57:35,017 --> 00:57:37,786
installation manager
Gary Winters.

1184
00:57:37,854 --> 00:57:39,521
Winters,
this is Commander Jarvis

1185
00:57:39,589 --> 00:57:41,523
of the U.S. Coast Guard
vessel Sherman.

1186
00:57:41,591 --> 00:57:42,624
Do you require assistance?

1187
00:57:42,692 --> 00:57:44,559
God, yes.
We are on fire.

1188
00:57:44,627 --> 00:57:47,161
I need to evacuate
approximately 105 men.

1189
00:57:47,229 --> 00:57:48,730
How far out are you?

1190
00:57:48,798 --> 00:57:49,898
Jarvis: The Sherman
will be on the scene

1191
00:57:49,966 --> 00:57:51,432
in approximately
30 minutes.

1192
00:57:51,501 --> 00:57:53,301
Begin staging
for evacuation.

1193
00:57:53,369 --> 00:57:54,903
Yes, sir.

1194
00:57:54,971 --> 00:57:58,807
Get all hands on deck
and prepare to evacuate
immediately.

1195
00:57:58,875 --> 00:58:00,441
We'll start
with the wounded.

1196
00:58:00,510 --> 00:58:01,910
Pull whatever guys
you need.

1197
00:58:01,978 --> 00:58:03,879
Grab firefighters
if you have to.

1198
00:58:03,946 --> 00:58:06,280
We're getting
off this rig.

1199
00:58:10,786 --> 00:58:13,788
No, this is
a natural phenomenon.

1200
00:58:13,856 --> 00:58:17,425
It--It's
a massive sinkhole.

1201
00:58:17,493 --> 00:58:19,160
Sinkhole? How?

1202
00:58:20,796 --> 00:58:23,164
This bedrock,
it's limestone.

1203
00:58:23,232 --> 00:58:24,533
It's turned to mush.

1204
00:58:24,600 --> 00:58:26,801
Yeah. The water
from the storm,
it's acidic.

1205
00:58:26,869 --> 00:58:28,202
Oil and drilling fluids.

1206
00:58:28,270 --> 00:58:29,771
Yeah, and it was draining
into the ground

1207
00:58:29,839 --> 00:58:32,173
and dissolving
the bedrock.

1208
00:58:32,241 --> 00:58:35,343
It's just like
exactly what happened
in Guatemala City.

1209
00:58:35,411 --> 00:58:37,012
Where does it go?

1210
00:58:37,079 --> 00:58:39,548
It's got to be
300 or 400 feet.

1211
00:58:39,615 --> 00:58:40,782
Listen, we got
to get out of here.

1212
00:58:40,850 --> 00:58:42,017
We got to get
back to the base.

1213
00:58:42,084 --> 00:58:42,951
Come on.

1214
00:58:43,019 --> 00:58:44,185
I can't believe
he's gone.

1215
00:58:44,253 --> 00:58:45,319
Come on!

1216
00:58:49,926 --> 00:58:51,826
Winters:
We're listing!

1217
00:58:51,894 --> 00:58:54,029
We're capsizing!

1218
00:58:58,434 --> 00:58:59,634
Come on.

1219
00:58:59,702 --> 00:59:00,969
We're gonna you
guys out of here.

1220
00:59:01,037 --> 00:59:03,071
Can I get
some help over here?

1221
00:59:04,239 --> 00:59:05,640
Jarvis, on radio:
Winters, come in.

1222
00:59:05,708 --> 00:59:07,943
There she is!
There's the Sherman!

1223
00:59:15,718 --> 00:59:17,085
Help!

1224
00:59:17,152 --> 00:59:19,187
Get all the wounded
down to the lower deck!

1225
00:59:19,254 --> 00:59:21,189
I want all hands
in life jackets!

1226
00:59:21,256 --> 00:59:22,724
What about
the firefighters?

1227
00:59:22,792 --> 00:59:23,959
We'll get everyone else
off first,

1228
00:59:24,026 --> 00:59:25,126
and they'll be the last
off the rig.

1229
00:59:25,194 --> 00:59:26,327
I don't want
to take any chances!

1230
00:59:26,395 --> 00:59:27,395
Good.

1231
00:59:27,463 --> 00:59:29,397
Why has the radio
gone dead?

1232
00:59:29,465 --> 00:59:31,265
Where is she?

1233
00:59:40,610 --> 00:59:42,077
Are you seeing this?

1234
00:59:44,346 --> 00:59:45,981
Take cover!

1235
00:59:48,884 --> 00:59:50,451
Move, move!

1236
00:59:53,522 --> 00:59:54,856
Hey, Travis, look!

1237
00:59:54,924 --> 00:59:55,857
Hey, help!
Hey!

1238
00:59:55,925 --> 00:59:57,892
Hey, help!

1239
00:59:58,861 --> 01:00:00,028
Hands up!

1240
01:00:02,197 --> 01:00:05,734
You're trespassing
on restricted property. Move.

1241
01:00:05,801 --> 01:00:06,968
No, no, no.
What are you
talking about?

1242
01:00:07,036 --> 01:00:08,302
Back up.
Let me explain.

1243
01:00:08,370 --> 01:00:10,171
I'm Dr. Jenna Sparks.

1244
01:00:10,239 --> 01:00:12,273
This is Travis Verdon.
What'd we do?

1245
01:00:12,341 --> 01:00:14,308
I'm placing both
of you under arrest.

1246
01:00:14,376 --> 01:00:15,476
For what?

1247
01:00:15,544 --> 01:00:17,311
You're trespassing
on a restricted area.

1248
01:00:17,379 --> 01:00:18,813
Pull the bed down.

1249
01:00:21,483 --> 01:00:22,751
Now hop up.

1250
01:00:27,990 --> 01:00:30,892
Now you,
put those on her.

1251
01:00:30,960 --> 01:00:32,326
Is this really necessary?

1252
01:00:32,394 --> 01:00:33,327
Do it now!

1253
01:00:35,731 --> 01:00:36,931
All right.

1254
01:00:39,802 --> 01:00:41,803
[Clicking]

1255
01:00:41,871 --> 01:00:43,437
All right.

1256
01:00:45,074 --> 01:00:48,242
Now you put those
on him behind his back.

1257
01:00:49,879 --> 01:00:52,147
Look, where are you
taking us?

1258
01:00:52,214 --> 01:00:53,347
Fort Irwin.

1259
01:00:53,415 --> 01:00:56,184
No, no! You have to take
us to Camp Pendleton.

1260
01:00:56,251 --> 01:00:57,952
Sorry, I'm taking you
to Fort Irwin.

1261
01:00:58,020 --> 01:00:59,754
Sir, she's trying to tell you
what we've been through.

1262
01:00:59,822 --> 01:01:01,056
Shut it!

1263
01:01:03,192 --> 01:01:05,560
I have two intruders
in custody.

1264
01:01:05,627 --> 01:01:06,961
I'll bring them in now.

1265
01:01:07,029 --> 01:01:09,731
Travis, he's taking us
to the wrong base.

1266
01:01:09,799 --> 01:01:11,733
My hands are too tight.
What?

1267
01:01:11,801 --> 01:01:12,767
You're gonna
have to do it.

1268
01:01:12,835 --> 01:01:14,035
Choke him out.
What?

1269
01:01:14,103 --> 01:01:15,536
Yeah, the element
of surprise.

1270
01:01:15,604 --> 01:01:16,637
Just get up
behind him

1271
01:01:16,706 --> 01:01:17,872
and stay
in control, okay?

1272
01:01:17,940 --> 01:01:18,973
You up for this?

1273
01:01:19,041 --> 01:01:20,241
Base, do you copy?

1274
01:01:20,309 --> 01:01:22,243
I'll just--I'll give you
the nod, all right?

1275
01:01:22,311 --> 01:01:23,411
All right.

1276
01:01:25,480 --> 01:01:28,983
All right,
now slide up in the bed.

1277
01:01:31,754 --> 01:01:32,721
I can't do it.
My hands are too tight.

1278
01:01:32,788 --> 01:01:34,522
You're gonna
have to help me.

1279
01:01:37,760 --> 01:01:38,993
Do it now!

1280
01:01:39,061 --> 01:01:40,829
[Jenna grunting]

1281
01:01:40,896 --> 01:01:42,130
[Choking]
Come on!
Cut me loose!

1282
01:01:42,198 --> 01:01:43,531
Okay!
Cut me loose!

1283
01:01:43,599 --> 01:01:44,699
Okay, okay!

1284
01:01:44,767 --> 01:01:46,534
Cut me loose, I said!

1285
01:01:49,638 --> 01:01:51,706
[Coughing]

1286
01:01:51,774 --> 01:01:53,742
All right, loosen him,
loosen him.

1287
01:01:53,809 --> 01:01:55,476
Okay.

1288
01:01:55,544 --> 01:01:56,677
Stay right there.

1289
01:01:56,746 --> 01:01:58,613
[Coughing]

1290
01:01:58,680 --> 01:02:00,481
All right.

1291
01:02:00,549 --> 01:02:03,118
Okay. Very slowly,

1292
01:02:03,185 --> 01:02:05,186
Get on your radio

1293
01:02:05,254 --> 01:02:08,923
and have them patch you
to Colonel Chadwick.

1294
01:02:09,792 --> 01:02:11,325
Do it now!

1295
01:02:11,393 --> 01:02:12,827
I need an emergency
patch-through

1296
01:02:12,895 --> 01:02:14,428
To Colonel Chadwick
at Pendleton.

1297
01:02:14,496 --> 01:02:16,064
[Coughs]

1298
01:02:20,002 --> 01:02:21,870
Is that an affirmative?

1299
01:02:21,937 --> 01:02:24,739
Then, yes, bring
Dr. Jenna Sparks
here immediately.

1300
01:02:24,807 --> 01:02:26,540
They're on the way.

1301
01:02:31,213 --> 01:02:34,548
[Alarm blaring]

1302
01:02:34,616 --> 01:02:35,884
[Coughing]

1303
01:02:39,488 --> 01:02:42,023
Structural support
is losing integrity.

1304
01:02:42,091 --> 01:02:44,725
Areas of the rig are
already collapsing.

1305
01:02:44,794 --> 01:02:45,994
How much time
do we have?

1306
01:02:46,061 --> 01:02:48,396
An hour, maybe two.

1307
01:02:50,199 --> 01:02:53,768
What are our options?

1308
01:02:53,836 --> 01:02:55,403
The Sherman was--

1309
01:02:55,470 --> 01:02:57,138
I don't even know
what I saw out there.

1310
01:02:57,206 --> 01:02:59,874
Our only hope
is rescue.

1311
01:02:59,942 --> 01:03:03,278
Alex, nobody's
coming for us.

1312
01:03:03,345 --> 01:03:06,915
We got to fight
if we want to save
our own lives.

1313
01:03:06,982 --> 01:03:08,482
Yes, sir.

1314
01:03:08,550 --> 01:03:11,585
Think. Now, is there
anything that you can do

1315
01:03:11,653 --> 01:03:13,521
to keep us
out of that lava?

1316
01:03:18,227 --> 01:03:19,828
The super cyclone
is turning

1317
01:03:19,895 --> 01:03:22,530
16 million
Southern Californians
into refugees.

1318
01:03:22,597 --> 01:03:23,932
There may be an option.

1319
01:03:23,999 --> 01:03:26,201
If you have any ideas,
doctor, now is the time.

1320
01:03:26,268 --> 01:03:27,635
It was
Dr. Cavanaugh's theory,

1321
01:03:27,703 --> 01:03:29,137
but I think
I can explain it.

1322
01:03:29,205 --> 01:03:30,404
This super cyclone
is unique

1323
01:03:30,472 --> 01:03:32,040
because its formation
was created by man.

1324
01:03:32,107 --> 01:03:33,507
How so?

1325
01:03:33,575 --> 01:03:35,910
Travis. He can best explain
what happened on that rig.

1326
01:03:35,978 --> 01:03:37,145
Yeah.

1327
01:03:37,213 --> 01:03:38,980
The Wilforce-3 was
designed to drill deeper

1328
01:03:39,048 --> 01:03:40,114
into the earth's crust

1329
01:03:40,182 --> 01:03:41,649
than any other rig
had gone before.

1330
01:03:41,717 --> 01:03:43,451
I mean, we knew
there would be
problems at first,

1331
01:03:43,518 --> 01:03:46,387
but we never saw
anything quite like this.

1332
01:03:51,526 --> 01:03:54,095
So what exactly
did happen out there?

1333
01:03:54,163 --> 01:03:57,031
Well, the drill pierced
the earth's crust,

1334
01:03:57,099 --> 01:04:01,736
broke into the mantle
and penetrated a magma pocket,

1335
01:04:01,803 --> 01:04:03,338
and the lava flowed
into the rig.

1336
01:04:03,405 --> 01:04:05,907
You synthesized
a super volcano.

1337
01:04:05,975 --> 01:04:09,710
This new super volcano,
it's bigger
than Mauna Loa.

1338
01:04:09,778 --> 01:04:12,013
So how does this volcano
tie into the storm?

1339
01:04:12,081 --> 01:04:15,783
The massive quantities
of lava elevated
the water temperature,

1340
01:04:15,851 --> 01:04:20,388
which created a low pressure
vortex around the Wilforce-3.

1341
01:04:20,455 --> 01:04:24,492
And now the atmosphere
around the rig
is highly unstable.

1342
01:04:24,559 --> 01:04:25,994
And your solution?

1343
01:04:26,061 --> 01:04:30,064
Well, if you
can deliver a payload

1344
01:04:30,132 --> 01:04:33,501
of silver iodide
nano-flakes into the storm,

1345
01:04:33,568 --> 01:04:37,071
we can generate
a controlled lightning strike
to break up the vortex.

1346
01:04:37,139 --> 01:04:39,573
How do you propose
we deliver this payload?

1347
01:04:39,641 --> 01:04:43,144
Do you have any pilot
who can navigate
under these conditions?

1348
01:04:43,212 --> 01:04:45,914
Dr. Sparks,
you're talking
about a suicide mission.

1349
01:04:45,981 --> 01:04:48,383
No, you don't
know that for sure.

1350
01:04:48,450 --> 01:04:50,418
The hurricane hunters
were able to....

1351
01:04:50,485 --> 01:04:52,853
Those planes fly
at 45,000 feet.

1352
01:04:52,922 --> 01:04:54,389
You're talking about
flying an F-16

1353
01:04:54,456 --> 01:04:56,724
directly into
the eye wall of a storm.

1354
01:04:56,792 --> 01:04:58,659
Colonel Chadwick, sir?

1355
01:04:58,727 --> 01:05:00,261
Sergeant Major?

1356
01:05:00,329 --> 01:05:03,597
Sir, I might have a man,
a pilot, who can do the job.

1357
01:05:03,665 --> 01:05:04,465
Who?

1358
01:05:04,533 --> 01:05:06,534
Lieutenant
Dave Connelly.

1359
01:05:06,601 --> 01:05:07,768
Connelly?

1360
01:05:07,836 --> 01:05:09,837
He's fresh
from combat, sir,

1361
01:05:09,905 --> 01:05:11,439
but I know
he can do the job.

1362
01:05:11,506 --> 01:05:13,107
He's an expert
in maneuvering.

1363
01:05:13,175 --> 01:05:14,909
He's just a kid.

1364
01:05:14,977 --> 01:05:16,744
He's
our only hope, sir.

1365
01:05:27,256 --> 01:05:30,358
Find him. Make sure
he knows the risks.

1366
01:05:30,426 --> 01:05:32,760
This
is volunteer only.

1367
01:05:32,828 --> 01:05:34,195
Yes, sir.

1368
01:05:48,743 --> 01:05:51,779
So, you need
someone crazy, huh?

1369
01:05:51,847 --> 01:05:52,813
Apparently.

1370
01:05:54,049 --> 01:05:56,250
The payload is secure.

1371
01:05:56,318 --> 01:05:58,119
When do I deploy?

1372
01:05:58,187 --> 01:06:00,054
The nano-flakes
must be released

1373
01:06:00,122 --> 01:06:01,856
as you enter
the eye wall of the storm.

1374
01:06:01,923 --> 01:06:04,258
That's where the electrical
charge is the strongest.

1375
01:06:04,326 --> 01:06:05,726
How will I know?

1376
01:06:05,794 --> 01:06:07,261
We'll track you
on radar.

1377
01:06:07,329 --> 01:06:10,131
We've established
a high-frequency
communication link.

1378
01:06:10,199 --> 01:06:11,632
I'll give you the signal
at the right time.

1379
01:06:11,700 --> 01:06:13,534
I'm ready to do
what needs to be done.

1380
01:06:13,602 --> 01:06:16,371
Son, if you're successful,
you'll save millions of lives.

1381
01:06:16,438 --> 01:06:17,505
My whole
family lives

1382
01:06:17,572 --> 01:06:19,007
in Southern
California, sir.

1383
01:06:19,074 --> 01:06:21,009
Good luck, Lieutenant.

1384
01:06:21,076 --> 01:06:23,177
Thank you, sir.

1385
01:06:50,472 --> 01:06:54,942
Okay, he's entering
the primary frontal boundary.

1386
01:06:55,010 --> 01:06:57,545
Approaching
target area.

1387
01:06:57,612 --> 01:06:58,913
You're doing great,
Lieutenant.

1388
01:06:58,980 --> 01:07:00,748
You'll be entering
the rain shield soon.

1389
01:07:00,815 --> 01:07:02,816
It's going
to get choppy.

1390
01:07:02,884 --> 01:07:04,152
Roger.

1391
01:07:04,219 --> 01:07:06,854
Once he can clear
the spiral bands,

1392
01:07:06,922 --> 01:07:09,290
he'll have
a straight shot
at the eye wall.

1393
01:07:09,358 --> 01:07:11,692
Hey, what's going on
with his radar tag?

1394
01:07:11,760 --> 01:07:12,826
[Beeping]

1395
01:07:13,929 --> 01:07:15,029
Lieutenant, come in.

1396
01:07:15,097 --> 01:07:16,497
[Radar beeping]

1397
01:07:16,565 --> 01:07:19,367
Connelly,
can you hear me?

1398
01:07:26,141 --> 01:07:29,710
Is there anything--
Anything we can do?

1399
01:07:31,380 --> 01:07:33,881
We gather the men,
we go to the highest ground.

1400
01:07:33,949 --> 01:07:36,817
Abandon our posts.

1401
01:07:36,885 --> 01:07:38,419
Go out fighting.

1402
01:07:38,487 --> 01:07:40,888
Fighting
is all we can do...

1403
01:07:40,956 --> 01:07:42,756
Sir.

1404
01:07:42,824 --> 01:07:44,492
Let's go.

1405
01:07:47,929 --> 01:07:49,497
[Alarm]

1406
01:07:51,900 --> 01:07:54,569
[Jet roaring]

1407
01:07:58,140 --> 01:07:59,840
It's an F-16!

1408
01:07:59,908 --> 01:08:02,210
Maybe it's another
rescue attempt.

1409
01:08:02,277 --> 01:08:03,944
Hold on.

1410
01:08:07,916 --> 01:08:09,484
[Radar beeping]

1411
01:08:12,121 --> 01:08:13,921
There! There he is!

1412
01:08:15,557 --> 01:08:17,825
Connelly, do you read?

1413
01:08:20,395 --> 01:08:21,762
Are you there?

1414
01:08:21,830 --> 01:08:25,065
Connelly:
Yes, ma'am. I'm flying
fast towards it.

1415
01:08:25,134 --> 01:08:26,700
Great, great.

1416
01:08:26,768 --> 01:08:28,636
Connelly,
you'll be approaching
the target area

1417
01:08:28,703 --> 01:08:32,340
in less
than two minutes.

1418
01:08:32,407 --> 01:08:34,175
Lieutenant,
this is Travis Verdon.

1419
01:08:34,243 --> 01:08:36,277
I'm an engineer
from the Wilforce-3 rig.

1420
01:08:36,345 --> 01:08:37,978
Can you see her?

1421
01:08:39,681 --> 01:08:41,782
There's something
there, sir.

1422
01:08:50,725 --> 01:08:52,926
Don't let go!

1423
01:08:52,994 --> 01:08:53,927
Take my hand!

1424
01:08:53,995 --> 01:08:55,163
Hold me!
I got you!

1425
01:08:55,230 --> 01:08:57,231
Hold me!
Don't let go!

1426
01:08:57,299 --> 01:08:58,932
Don't let it go!

1427
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:00,134
Aah!
No!

1428
01:09:00,202 --> 01:09:01,735
Aah!

1429
01:09:08,243 --> 01:09:10,444
Aah!

1430
01:09:18,320 --> 01:09:20,754
Connelly,
what do you see?

1431
01:09:20,822 --> 01:09:23,924
A lake of fire,
lava flares.

1432
01:09:45,847 --> 01:09:49,517
I never thought
it'd end like this.

1433
01:09:49,585 --> 01:09:50,718
It's been an honor.

1434
01:09:50,785 --> 01:09:51,885
You, too, sir.

1435
01:09:51,953 --> 01:09:53,887
[Screaming]

1436
01:09:53,955 --> 01:09:56,190
I guess there's some fights
you just don't win.

1437
01:09:56,258 --> 01:09:57,725
We tried.

1438
01:09:57,792 --> 01:09:58,959
Yes, sir.

1439
01:10:01,196 --> 01:10:02,863
So how do we do this?

1440
01:10:04,299 --> 01:10:07,101
Jump.

1441
01:10:07,168 --> 01:10:10,037
I don't think
I can do this, Gary!

1442
01:10:10,105 --> 01:10:12,773
Yeah, you can.

1443
01:10:12,841 --> 01:10:14,842
Just let go.

1444
01:10:16,878 --> 01:10:18,679
[Screaming]

1445
01:10:22,351 --> 01:10:25,953
[Screaming]

1446
01:10:27,188 --> 01:10:28,956
[Screaming]

1447
01:10:37,466 --> 01:10:39,400
[Screaming]

1448
01:11:00,289 --> 01:11:01,955
Few more seconds.

1449
01:11:03,425 --> 01:11:07,161
Okay, Connelly,
t-minus 10,

1450
01:11:07,228 --> 01:11:08,228
9,

1451
01:11:08,297 --> 01:11:10,464
8...

1452
01:11:13,402 --> 01:11:15,269
Jenna: 7,

1453
01:11:15,337 --> 01:11:16,304
6,

1454
01:11:16,371 --> 01:11:18,906
5,

1455
01:11:18,973 --> 01:11:20,308
4,

1456
01:11:20,375 --> 01:11:23,076
3...

1457
01:11:23,144 --> 01:11:24,211
No!

1458
01:11:24,279 --> 01:11:25,279
Where's
his radar tag?

1459
01:11:25,347 --> 01:11:27,014
Where's Connelly?

1460
01:11:27,081 --> 01:11:28,982
The flare. He's gone.

1461
01:11:29,050 --> 01:11:30,418
Chadwick:
Connelly, come in.

1462
01:11:30,485 --> 01:11:33,987
Connelly--Connelly,
do you read?

1463
01:11:34,055 --> 01:11:35,155
No!

1464
01:11:35,223 --> 01:11:36,256
Oh, my god.

1465
01:11:36,325 --> 01:11:38,526
He was our last hope.

1466
01:11:41,530 --> 01:11:42,797
He was a hero.

1467
01:11:42,864 --> 01:11:45,499
Travis: The Wilforce-3,
she's gone.

1468
01:11:48,470 --> 01:11:52,873
Sir, the storm,
it's moving inland.

1469
01:11:59,514 --> 01:12:00,914
Sir, you got to listen!

1470
01:12:00,982 --> 01:12:02,282
There's got to be
a manmade force

1471
01:12:02,351 --> 01:12:03,884
powerful enough
to stop this.

1472
01:12:03,952 --> 01:12:05,786
Unless there's some way
to convince our boys from Thule

1473
01:12:05,854 --> 01:12:07,054
to drag an iceberg
down here from Greenland,

1474
01:12:07,121 --> 01:12:08,556
I'm gonna have to tell
the General

1475
01:12:08,623 --> 01:12:09,990
that the situation's fubar.

1476
01:12:10,058 --> 01:12:11,425
Wait, wait, wait,
I've got an idea!

1477
01:12:11,493 --> 01:12:14,495
Dr. Sparks, I appreciate
your enthusiasm,

1478
01:12:14,563 --> 01:12:16,230
But I just had one
of my top pilots

1479
01:12:16,297 --> 01:12:19,333
Fly an F-16
into a super volcano
for nothing!

1480
01:12:19,401 --> 01:12:21,134
Colonel.
Colonel, wait, please!

1481
01:12:21,202 --> 01:12:22,670
You've got to listen!

1482
01:12:22,738 --> 01:12:24,037
Bring
in the generators.

1483
01:12:24,105 --> 01:12:26,707
No, sir, Huntington Beach
is out of commission.

1484
01:12:26,775 --> 01:12:28,609
Jenna:
Colonel! Colonel?

1485
01:12:28,677 --> 01:12:29,977
You have to listen.

1486
01:12:30,044 --> 01:12:31,512
What, Dr. Sparks?

1487
01:12:31,580 --> 01:12:33,080
We need to go
on one more mission.

1488
01:12:33,147 --> 01:12:34,482
Absolutely not.
I'm not gonna let

1489
01:12:34,549 --> 01:12:36,049
another man fly
to his death.

1490
01:12:36,117 --> 01:12:37,951
You won't have to.
I'll go, sir.

1491
01:12:38,019 --> 01:12:39,052
Me, too.

1492
01:12:39,120 --> 01:12:40,721
What kind
of a mission

1493
01:12:40,789 --> 01:12:42,256
are you guys
talking about?

1494
01:12:42,323 --> 01:12:45,259
We need to deprive the storm
of its energy source.

1495
01:12:45,326 --> 01:12:47,160
This storm is
completely uncontrollable.

1496
01:12:47,228 --> 01:12:48,262
You've seen that.

1497
01:12:48,329 --> 01:12:50,030
We use liquid nitrogen.

1498
01:12:50,098 --> 01:12:51,198
It'll form a plug,

1499
01:12:51,266 --> 01:12:53,967
stop the flow of lava,
and cool the water.

1500
01:12:54,035 --> 01:12:56,804
How are we gonna get
liquid nitrogen
to the site?

1501
01:12:56,872 --> 01:12:58,773
We'll take it
in a liquefied
natural gas tanker.

1502
01:12:58,840 --> 01:13:00,974
It's like a giant thermos
with a pumping system.

1503
01:13:01,042 --> 01:13:02,443
Where
are we gonna find

1504
01:13:02,511 --> 01:13:04,612
one of these giant
thermos tankers?

1505
01:13:04,679 --> 01:13:06,614
Petro-Cal in long beach
has one right now.

1506
01:13:06,681 --> 01:13:07,848
Who's gonna drive it?

1507
01:13:07,916 --> 01:13:09,884
I will, sir.

1508
01:13:09,951 --> 01:13:12,352
So how you gonna
keep it from melting?

1509
01:13:12,421 --> 01:13:15,656
The ocean currents
are moving the lava
to the East,

1510
01:13:15,724 --> 01:13:17,525
so there's
a small corridor of water

1511
01:13:17,592 --> 01:13:18,526
that would allow
the tanker passage,

1512
01:13:18,593 --> 01:13:21,261
but it won't last long.

1513
01:13:21,329 --> 01:13:23,230
Yeah, but if I can get
in there with the tanker,

1514
01:13:23,298 --> 01:13:25,132
I could
deliver the payload.

1515
01:13:25,199 --> 01:13:26,199
How you gonna get out?

1516
01:13:26,267 --> 01:13:27,334
A chopper evac.

1517
01:13:27,402 --> 01:13:29,837
I see.

1518
01:13:29,905 --> 01:13:32,339
Using the size
of the original

1519
01:13:32,407 --> 01:13:33,841
bore hole conduit

1520
01:13:33,909 --> 01:13:36,944
and factoring in the expanse
of the lava throat...

1521
01:13:39,380 --> 01:13:43,984
135,000 cubic meters would
generate a substantial plug.

1522
01:13:44,052 --> 01:13:45,986
Yeah, tanker Euclides
would do it.

1523
01:13:46,054 --> 01:13:47,287
And I'll be
on the tanker

1524
01:13:47,355 --> 01:13:49,156
monitoring
the atmospheric conditions.

1525
01:13:49,223 --> 01:13:51,625
I'll know exactly
when the storm is destroyed.

1526
01:13:51,693 --> 01:13:53,928
Is this
a permanent solution?

1527
01:13:53,995 --> 01:13:55,195
Yes, sir.

1528
01:13:55,263 --> 01:13:56,597
Yes, permanent.

1529
01:13:56,665 --> 01:14:01,034
Where we gonna find
135,000 cubic meters
of liquid nitrogen?

1530
01:14:01,102 --> 01:14:02,202
Vandenberg.

1531
01:14:02,270 --> 01:14:04,505
They've got huge tanks
of liquid nitrogen out there

1532
01:14:04,573 --> 01:14:06,373
for the rocket
launches, sir.

1533
01:14:06,441 --> 01:14:08,208
And once the cool water

1534
01:14:08,276 --> 01:14:10,578
sucks the energy
out of the super cyclone,

1535
01:14:10,645 --> 01:14:12,379
it will be more
like a thunderstorm

1536
01:14:12,447 --> 01:14:14,348
rather than hurricane.

1537
01:14:14,415 --> 01:14:16,283
What do you think, sir?

1538
01:14:20,421 --> 01:14:22,623
I think
if you're wrong...

1539
01:14:22,691 --> 01:14:25,559
Most of the West Coast
is gonna die,

1540
01:14:25,627 --> 01:14:27,728
including us.

1541
01:14:45,547 --> 01:14:47,280
Colonel.

1542
01:14:47,348 --> 01:14:49,049
Once we arrive on site,
the crew will have

1543
01:14:49,117 --> 01:14:51,051
less than 15 minutes
to deploy the l.N.

1544
01:14:51,119 --> 01:14:53,020
before our window closes
and the lava

1545
01:14:53,087 --> 01:14:55,288
completely destroys
the tanker's outer hull.

1546
01:14:55,356 --> 01:14:58,058
I'll be controlling
a laser-guided
targeting system

1547
01:14:58,126 --> 01:14:59,593
to navigate
the payload drop

1548
01:14:59,661 --> 01:15:01,294
so we can make
every second count.

1549
01:15:01,362 --> 01:15:03,564
The chopper will
be sure to evacuate
you and your team

1550
01:15:03,632 --> 01:15:05,065
off the tanker
before she goes down.

1551
01:15:05,133 --> 01:15:06,500
Yeah, it's gonna be
a rough ride

1552
01:15:06,568 --> 01:15:08,135
no matter how we time it.

1553
01:15:08,202 --> 01:15:10,203
Yeah, well,
we're cutting it very close,

1554
01:15:10,271 --> 01:15:11,071
so we better get going.

1555
01:15:11,139 --> 01:15:12,673
Yep, this is it.
Good luck.

1556
01:15:12,741 --> 01:15:14,041
Thank you.

1557
01:15:14,108 --> 01:15:15,409
Hey, Travis,
you control the nav,

1558
01:15:15,476 --> 01:15:16,510
and I'll take
care of operations.

1559
01:15:16,578 --> 01:15:17,711
Okay.

1560
01:15:19,480 --> 01:15:21,214
Chadwick:
What's the status?

1561
01:15:21,282 --> 01:15:23,383
The Euclides
is on its way, sir.

1562
01:15:23,451 --> 01:15:25,619
[Radio chatter]

1563
01:15:25,687 --> 01:15:27,354
They're gonna thread
the needle

1564
01:15:27,422 --> 01:15:28,856
through that cooler water.

1565
01:15:28,924 --> 01:15:31,191
Even with a ship
that size, sir...

1566
01:15:32,694 --> 01:15:35,195
This storm is a monster.

1567
01:15:44,573 --> 01:15:48,208
Yeah, Colonel,
we're approaching target area.

1568
01:15:51,312 --> 01:15:56,584
Crew, prepare
to deploy liquid nitrogen.

1569
01:15:56,651 --> 01:15:58,085
Travis, on loudspeaker:
Open the valve on the pump

1570
01:15:58,152 --> 01:16:00,287
and load the l.N.
into the sprayer.

1571
01:16:00,354 --> 01:16:03,256
Be careful, boys,
there's a lot
of pressure down there.

1572
01:16:06,160 --> 01:16:08,195
[Rattling]

1573
01:16:18,640 --> 01:16:19,974
Travis, something's wrong.

1574
01:16:20,041 --> 01:16:22,309
The hull is dissolving
too quickly.

1575
01:16:26,514 --> 01:16:29,249
The current
is pulling us off course.

1576
01:16:29,317 --> 01:16:31,118
We're losing our window.

1577
01:16:32,654 --> 01:16:34,221
We're caught
in a whirlpool!

1578
01:16:34,288 --> 01:16:36,423
The current
is pulling us under!

1579
01:16:41,930 --> 01:16:43,530
Colonel,
we're in trouble!

1580
01:16:43,598 --> 01:16:44,999
Send the chopper now!

1581
01:16:45,967 --> 01:16:48,468
Deploy
rescue chopper now!

1582
01:16:48,536 --> 01:16:51,471
Colonel? Colonel!

1583
01:16:58,312 --> 01:17:00,213
Rescue chopper
is en route, Jenna!

1584
01:17:00,281 --> 01:17:01,381
It's en route!

1585
01:17:01,449 --> 01:17:04,752
Position the sprayer
and release the valve.

1586
01:17:04,819 --> 01:17:06,954
Crewman:
Valve released.

1587
01:17:07,822 --> 01:17:10,858
It's too hot!
It's too hot!

1588
01:17:13,762 --> 01:17:16,830
Deploy the l.N. Now!

1589
01:17:26,775 --> 01:17:28,676
The temperatures
are dropping.

1590
01:17:28,743 --> 01:17:30,177
[Metal creaking]

1591
01:17:33,314 --> 01:17:34,381
Uhh!

1592
01:17:34,448 --> 01:17:36,050
[Gasps]

1593
01:17:38,053 --> 01:17:41,421
The hull's breached,
but it's too soon.

1594
01:17:41,489 --> 01:17:42,489
Something's wrong.

1595
01:17:49,964 --> 01:17:51,865
She's on auto-pilot.

1596
01:17:51,933 --> 01:17:53,867
She's circling
with the whirlpool.

1597
01:17:53,935 --> 01:17:55,302
[Squeaking]

1598
01:17:55,369 --> 01:17:56,536
[Hissing]

1599
01:17:56,604 --> 01:17:58,471
[Bolt explodes]

1600
01:17:58,539 --> 01:18:01,075
Travis: Delivering the l.N.
until she goes down.

1601
01:18:03,011 --> 01:18:05,378
Something's
definitely not right.

1602
01:18:05,446 --> 01:18:07,181
Time to evacuate!

1603
01:18:10,085 --> 01:18:11,484
All hands topside!

1604
01:18:11,552 --> 01:18:13,053
We are evacuating!

1605
01:18:13,121 --> 01:18:15,022
Prepare
to abandon ship!

1606
01:18:15,090 --> 01:18:18,291
Prepare
to abandon ship!

1607
01:18:18,359 --> 01:18:20,627
The temperatures
are rising again!

1608
01:18:20,695 --> 01:18:21,795
Okay,
we got to go now!

1609
01:18:21,863 --> 01:18:23,296
Travis: Yeah,
go topside and make sure

1610
01:18:23,364 --> 01:18:25,065
all the men
are accounted for.

1611
01:18:26,801 --> 01:18:29,603
All right. Travis,
don't be long, okay?

1612
01:18:29,670 --> 01:18:31,571
We don't have
much time left.

1613
01:18:47,555 --> 01:18:49,823
Travis, where are you?

1614
01:18:49,891 --> 01:18:51,324
[Creaking]

1615
01:18:51,392 --> 01:18:54,128
Travis, get up here!

1616
01:18:54,195 --> 01:18:55,863
No! We got
to wait for him!

1617
01:18:55,930 --> 01:18:57,330
There's one more man!

1618
01:18:57,398 --> 01:18:58,465
Travis!

1619
01:19:02,003 --> 01:19:04,437
Travis, can you hear me?

1620
01:19:09,778 --> 01:19:11,344
No, there's
one more man!

1621
01:19:11,412 --> 01:19:13,113
Get us out of here!

1622
01:19:13,181 --> 01:19:14,915
We can't leave him!

1623
01:19:21,355 --> 01:19:23,390
Reporter:
36 hours of steady rainfall

1624
01:19:23,457 --> 01:19:25,025
has left many homes
in the metro area

1625
01:19:25,093 --> 01:19:26,827
knee-deep in floodwaters.

1626
01:19:26,895 --> 01:19:29,396
Temperatures
are normalizing.

1627
01:19:30,698 --> 01:19:33,333
The storm's breaking up.

1628
01:19:33,401 --> 01:19:36,236
[Thunder]

1629
01:19:36,304 --> 01:19:38,138
Mobilize
search and rescue

1630
01:19:38,206 --> 01:19:39,539
and get the governor
on the phone.

1631
01:19:39,607 --> 01:19:40,908
Is this over?

1632
01:19:40,975 --> 01:19:43,076
Is this really over?

1633
01:19:47,148 --> 01:19:49,649
Congratulations,
Colonel.

1634
01:19:49,717 --> 01:19:51,518
Let's hope it sticks.

1635
01:19:58,193 --> 01:20:00,627
The super cyclone's
breaking up!

1636
01:20:04,732 --> 01:20:06,066
I'm so sorry.

1637
01:20:07,135 --> 01:20:10,103
You did it, Travis.

1638
01:20:30,658 --> 01:20:32,025
[Sighs]

1639
01:20:43,637 --> 01:20:47,374
Must have gotten
pretty hairy
on that tanker.

1640
01:20:47,441 --> 01:20:49,376
Dr. Flynn, uh,

1641
01:20:49,443 --> 01:20:52,579
if you don't mind,
I'd rather be alone.

1642
01:20:54,182 --> 01:20:56,116
Okay, yeah, um...

1643
01:20:56,184 --> 01:20:59,152
I totally understand.

1644
01:20:59,220 --> 01:21:03,991
I'll just be below decks
if you need me.

1645
01:21:04,058 --> 01:21:05,759
Thank you.

1646
01:21:32,153 --> 01:21:36,089
Captain Worley,
10:00, do you see it?

1647
01:21:37,758 --> 01:21:38,758
Yes, I do.

1648
01:21:47,601 --> 01:21:48,701
What's going on?

1649
01:21:48,769 --> 01:21:49,937
There's something out there.

1650
01:21:50,004 --> 01:21:51,038
What is it?

1651
01:21:51,105 --> 01:21:52,272
I don't know,

1652
01:21:52,340 --> 01:21:54,174
but we're gonna go closer
to take a look.

1653
01:22:02,716 --> 01:22:04,451
It's a person!

1654
01:22:04,518 --> 01:22:06,753
Captain Worley,
do you see it?

1655
01:22:06,821 --> 01:22:09,122
It's a person!

1656
01:22:09,190 --> 01:22:12,159
I see it! I see it!

1657
01:22:13,227 --> 01:22:15,728
Worley: Throw the net.

1658
01:22:15,796 --> 01:22:20,500
Let's reel him in.

1659
01:22:25,840 --> 01:22:28,675
[Winch grinding]

1660
01:22:38,152 --> 01:22:39,552
Jenna: Is it him?

1661
01:22:40,855 --> 01:22:42,255
It is him!

1662
01:22:42,323 --> 01:22:43,656
Travis, it is you!

1663
01:22:43,724 --> 01:22:45,092
He's alive.

1664
01:22:45,159 --> 01:22:47,827
Go get some water
and a blanket.

1665
01:22:47,895 --> 01:22:49,729
You're gonna be fine.

1666
01:22:49,797 --> 01:22:50,830
You're gonna
be okay.

1667
01:22:50,898 --> 01:22:52,165
Travis,
can you hear me?

1668
01:22:52,233 --> 01:22:53,566
Okay,
can you get up?

1669
01:22:53,634 --> 01:22:56,769
Yeah. Give me a hand.
All right.

1670
01:23:01,575 --> 01:23:04,144
Captain Worley?
Yeah, we got him.

1671
01:23:04,212 --> 01:23:06,346
Take us back.

1672
01:23:06,414 --> 01:23:08,915
Aye, aye, Dr. Sparks,

1673
01:23:08,983 --> 01:23:10,517
With pleasure.

1674
01:23:15,589 --> 01:23:16,990
Here.

1675
01:23:17,058 --> 01:23:18,625
Travis?

1676
01:23:18,692 --> 01:23:21,528
Travis, come on.

1677
01:23:24,932 --> 01:23:27,501
All right, easy, easy.

1678
01:23:29,670 --> 01:23:32,772
Watch your foot,
watch your foot.

1679
01:23:32,840 --> 01:23:34,474
Okay.

1680
01:23:57,898 --> 01:23:59,299
Hey, uh...

1681
01:24:01,102 --> 01:24:03,570
Thanks for
not giving up on me.

1682
01:24:03,637 --> 01:24:05,605
You're welcome.

1683
01:24:09,977 --> 01:24:13,547
Hey, look, a rainbow.

1684
01:24:16,451 --> 01:24:19,419
Actually, it's, um,

1685
01:24:19,487 --> 01:24:21,555
a circumhorizontal arc.

1686
01:24:21,622 --> 01:24:23,690
It's the off-gassing
of liquid nitrogen,

1687
01:24:23,757 --> 01:24:27,994
and it creates
these, um, plate-shaped
crystals in the clouds.

1688
01:24:28,062 --> 01:24:29,796
It's amazing, huh?

1689
01:24:29,863 --> 01:24:30,830
Yeah.

1690
01:24:35,002 --> 01:24:37,370
It's beautiful.

